  "chunk_index": 7,
  "summary": "After Inspector Rives and a forensic officer conclude that Hubert Litcham Rock’s death was a suicide—citing the locked doors and windows, the deceased's eccentric behavior, and a bullet found below a mirror—Hercule Poirot begins his own investigation. Using a flashlight, Poirot discovers four footprints in a flower bed outside the study window. He observes that the prints belong to small, delicate shoes with high heels, which leads him to question Diana Clifes.\n\nPoirot confronts Diana in the morning room. She admits to being in the garden around 7:00 PM and again at 8:15 PM to pick flowers, noting that she attempted to climb through the study window but found it locked. Poirot presents her with the tiny silk rosebud he previously found in Jeffrey Keene's pocket; Diana claims the item came from her purse.\n\nPoirot gathers the household in the study, including Mr. Baring, Jeffrey Keene, Major John Marshall, Joan Ashby, Harry Dahlhausen, and the butler, Mr. Digby. He rejects the suicide verdict, arguing that Mr. Rock's megalomania would have prevented him from taking his own life. Poirot demonstrates that the study window's latch is loose and can be easily locked from the outside without turning the handle. Finally, he addresses the distribution of the estate: Mrs. Litcham Rock is to receive an annual income and a house, while the remainder of the property goes to Diana, provided her future husband adopts the family name.",
